The '''Undersea and Hyperbaric Medical Society''' ('''UHMS''') is the primary source of information for [[Diving medicine|diving]] and [[hyperbaric medicine|hyperbaric]] medicine physiology worldwide.

==History==
The Undersea Medical Society (UMS) grew from the close associations of a small group of scientists. These men realized after a series of ''International Symposia on Underwater Physiology'', initiated by the [[University of Pennsylvania]] and the [[Office of Naval Research]] that there was a need to stimulate in the field of undersea medicine.<ref name=UHMShx>{{cite book |author=Chandler, Donald |title=Undersea and Hyperbaric Medical Society 1967 - 2007: A history of 40 years. |publisher=Undersea and Hyperbaric Medical Society |page=59}}</ref><ref name=ISUPaid>{{cite web |author=staff |title=Underwater Physiology Symposium Finding Aid |publisher=[[Rubicon Foundation]] |url=http://rubicon-foundation.org/underwater-physiology-symposiums/ |accessdate=2009-06-11 }}</ref> This group consisted of [[Diving medicine|diving]] and [[Aviation medicine|aerospace]] Dr's Edward L. Beckman, Jack L. Kinsey, [[Christian J. Lambertsen]], Walter F. Mazzone, Earl H. Ninow, and Robert D. Workman.<ref name=UHMShx/> The key decision from this meeting was that Dr. Lambertsen was charged with writing the [[Constitution (corporate)|Constitution]] and establishing the Society.<ref name=UHMShx/> They also decided that the [[Aerospace Medical Association]] could be the initial home of the UMS.<ref name=UHMShx/>

On 10 April 1967, a meeting was held in [[Washington, D.C.]] to introduce the charter membership and elect the Society officers and Executive committee.<ref name=UHMShx/> There were 88 charter members and the founding Executive committee was made up of Dr's Edward L. Beckman, [[Albert R. Behnke]], [[George F. Bond]], Wallace O. Fenn, Jack L. Kinsey, [[Christian J. Lambertsen]], Walter F. Mazzone, Earl H. Ninow, Heinz R. Schreiner, and Robert D. Workman.<ref name=UHMShx/><!-- need 1967 Aerospace Medicine Journal announcement -->

By 1973, the UMS had grown to the point of needing an office and hired [[Charles Wesley Shilling|Charles W. Shilling]] as the first Executive secretary.<ref name=UHMShx/> By the next year, the UMS established its scientific journal, ''[[Undersea Biomedical Research]]''.<ref name=UHMShx/><ref name=RRRubr>{{cite web |title=Undersea Biomedical Research Journal collection |author=UHMS |publisher=Rubicon Foundation, Inc |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/2424 |accessdate=2009-06-11 }}</ref> The journal continued under this name until 1993 when it was changed to ''[[Undersea and Hyperbaric Medicine Journal]]''.<ref name=RRRuhm>{{cite web |title=Undersea and Hyperbaric Medicine Journal collection |author=UHMS |publisher=Rubicon Foundation, Inc |url=http://archive.rubicon-foundation.org/1811 |accessdate=2009-06-11 }}</ref>

In 1986, the UMS changed its name to the current one.  The name change reflected the rapidly growing interest in hyperbaric oxygen physiology and therapy.<ref name=UHMShx/>  The UHMS's purpose is to provide scientific information to protect the  health of [[Scuba diving|sport]], [[Frogman|military]] and [[Professional diving|commercial]] divers and to improve the scientific basis of hyperbaric oxygen [[hyperbaric medicine|therapy]], promote sound treatment protocols and standards of practice and provide [[Continuing medical education|CME]] accreditation within its field.

==Indications for hyperbaric oxygen==
UHMS definition of Hyperbaric Oxygen Therapy (HBO):
The patient breathes 100% [[oxygen]] [[Intermittency|intermittently]] while the [[pressure]] of the treatment [[Pressure vessel|chamber]] is increased to greater than one atmosphere absolute ([[Relative pressure|atm abs]]). Current information indicates that pressurization should be at least 1.4 atm abs. This may occur in a single person chamber (monoplace) or multiplace chamber (may hold 2 or more people). Breathing 100% oxygen at 1 atm abs or exposing isolated parts of the body to 100% oxygen does not constitute HBO therapy.

